    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nNeovim's default Lua `package.path` includes `./?.lua` as the first search path, which means `require()` will load Lua modules from the current working directory before searching the runtime path. This is a **security vulnerability** that allows arbitrary code execution when running Neovim from an untrusted directory.\n\nWhen a plugin calls `require(\"modulename\")`, if a file named `modulename.lua` exists in the current directory, it will be loaded instead of the intended plugin module. This can lead to:\n\n1. **Arbitrary code execution** - An attacker who can place files in a directory can execute arbitrary Lua code when a victim runs `nvim` from that directory\n2. **Module hijacking** - Common module names like `notify`, `json`, `utils`, `async`, etc. can be intercepted\n3. **Silent exploitation** - The malicious file executes before any user configuration or security measures\n\n### Example Attack Scenario\n\nA malicious `notify.lua` file in the current directory:\n```lua\n-- This file is in the current working directory\nvim.notify(\"Test\")  -- Could be replaced with malicious code\n```\n\nNote this was partially reported in https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/22273, but since it's a security issue I decided to open a new issue.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create a test file in a directory:\n```bash\nmkdir -p /tmp/testdir\ncd /tmp/testdir\necho 'vim.notify(\"Malicious code executed!\")' > notify.lua\n```\n\n2. Run Neovim with a clean config:\n```bash\nnvim --clean\n```\n\n3. Inside Neovim, execute:\n```lua\n:lua print(package.path)\n```\n\nOutput shows `./?.lua` as the first entry:\n```\n./?.lua\n/usr/share/luajit-2.1/?.lua\n...\n```\n\n4. Verify the vulnerability by checking which module is loaded:\n```bash\ncd /tmp/testdir\nnvim --clean -c \"lua local ok, mod = pcall(require, 'notify'); print('Loaded:', ok)\" -c \"qa\"\n```\n\nOutput:\n```\nMalicious code executed!\nLoaded: true\n```\n\n5. Verify the loader order:\n```bash\ncd /tmp/testdir\nnvim --clean -c \"lua local loaders = package.loaders; for i=1,#loaders do local ok, result = pcall(loaders[i], 'notify'); print('loader', i, type(result)) end\" -c \"qa\"\n```\n\nThe C loader (loader 5) finds and executes `./notify.lua` before any runtime path search.\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nNeovim should **not** include the current working directory (`./?.lua`) in `package.path` by default. The module search should be restricted to:\n\n1. `package.preload`\n2. Neovim's runtime path (`vim.loader`)\n3. Plugin-specific paths\n4. System Lua libraries\n\nThis is particularly important because:\n- Neovim is often used to edit untrusted files\n- Users frequently run `nvim` from various directories. For example a repository you cloned.\n- Plugins use common module names that could be hijacked\n- The `exrc` feature requires explicit opt-in for security, but `./?.lua` in `package.path` bypasses this protection\n\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.1 Build type: RelWithDebInfo LuaJIT 2.1.1774896198\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, vim does not support lua\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArch Linux\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nAlacritty\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\npacman",
