            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> finds and executes `./notify.lua` before any runtime path search.\n\nIt appears that vim scans `'runtimepath'` for lua files before checking `package.path`.\n\nWhile I can reproduce the example you have given, it seems that `./notify.lua` is only executed if there is no module named `notify` anywhere on `'runtimepath'`. I'd still consider this a security vulnerability that needs to be fixed, but for it to be exploited by an attacker, the attacker would need `require('notify')` to be run by the user or the config and not find any other file first.\n\nFor example, if you remove the `--clean` from your example, and then create a file in your config named `lua/notify.lua`, the exploit breaks.\n\nFor this reason it is impossible to replace core `require'vim.whatever'` files with malicious ones (as far as my testing goes), and the only way to replace `require`s from a plugin or config is if that plugin or config is not on the runtimepath (for example, with `nvim --clean`). But of course, if you're using `nvim --clean`, it's unlikely for anything to be `require`d in the first place.\n\nStill, there's no good reason for `./?.lua` to be a part of `package.path`, and it's very possible that there's an exception I haven't found that could be used to load malicious code without manually running `require(badfilename)`. For instance, any (third-party) plugin which selectively checks for other plugins via `pcall(require, ...)` would be vulnerable.",
