            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Yes, Lazy messes with the runtimepath in an intrusive way, so any example relying on lazy.nvim is not an issue (for us -- raise it with them).\n\nAnd `vim` modules are compiled into the Nvim binary, so it's indeed not possible to shadow them locally.\n\nAlso, `nvim` is intended to be used as a standalone Lua runtime (via `nvim -l`), where `./?.lua` may be required, so hardening is more complicated than simply force-removing `/?.lua` from `package.path` internally.",
