            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Yes, I should have reported this as security issue, but since the bug has been reported and known for 3 years I didn't. And now it's even more so, I'm continuing the discussion here.\n\n> This behavior has been fine when used in standalone lua, python, cmd.exe and many many other scripting languages for multiple decades.\n\nThat's a different scenario, the script does not magically run when you enter a directory, or open an unrelated script in an editor. Here's the exploit can happen for example when you clone a repository  and open up nvim to look at it, perhaps even with the intent of investigating security issues.\n\nNOTE: `exrc` can do the similar things and described in `:help trojan-horse`, but that has to be explicitly allowed by the user.\n\nAnyway, here's an example without `lazy.nvim` that uses a real plugin [nvim-tree.lua](https://github.com/nvim-tree/nvim-tree.lua), which optionally depends on [nvim-web-devicons](https://github.com/nvim-tree/nvim-web-devicons) via `pcall(require, \"nvim-web-devicons\")`. (note there are many other plugins that similarly depends on other optional plugins) When nvim-web-devicons is not installed, `package.path` is searched, and `./?.lua` matches a malicious file in the current directory.\n\n1. Create `minimal.lua`\n\n```lua\nlocal install_path = vim.fn.fnamemodify(\"nvim_issue/nvim-tree.lua\", \":p\")\nif vim.fn.isdirectory(install_path) == 0 then\n  vim.fn.system({\n    \"git\",\n    \"clone\",\n    \"--depth=1\",\n    \"https://github.com/nvim-tree/nvim-tree.lua.git\",\n    install_path,\n  })\nend\nvim.opt.runtimepath:append(install_path)\n\nrequire(\"nvim-tree\").setup({})\n\nvim.schedule(function()\n  require(\"nvim-tree.api\").tree.open()\n  vim.schedule(function()\n    vim.cmd(\"qa!\")\n  end)\nend)\n```\n\n2. Create a malicious `nvim-web-devicons.lua` in the current directory:\n\n```lua\nlocal M = {}\n\nfunction M.setup()\n  print(\"HIJACKED: malicious nvim-web-devicons loaded from ./?.lua!\")\nend\n\nfunction M.get_icon(name, ext, opts)\n  return \"?\", \"ErrorMsg\"\nend\n\nreturn M\n```\n\n3. Run Neovim from the directory containing the malicious file:\n\n```sh\nnvim --headless --clean -u minimal.lua\n```\n\n**Expected output:** nothing (the malicious file should not be loaded)\n\n**Actual output:** `HIJACKED: malicious nvim-web-devicons loaded from ./?.lua!`\n",
