        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> 1. Create `minimal.lua`\n\nThis example also works when using `vim.pack` to install packages:\n\n```lua\nvim.pack.add {\n  \"https://github.com/nvim-tree/nvim-tree.lua.git\",\n}\n\nrequire(\"nvim-tree\").setup({})\n\nvim.schedule(function()\n  require(\"nvim-tree.api\").tree.open()\nend)\n```\n\n<img width=\"865\" height=\"561\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/fefb783b-3669-4b24-b722-c5b34f15d50e\" />\n\n> Also, `nvim` is intended to be used as a standalone Lua runtime (via `nvim -l`), where `./?.lua` may be required, so hardening is more complicated than simply force-removing `/?.lua` from `package.path` internally.\n\nAn exception can be made for `nvim -l`, but the default `package.path` needs to be modified. This is a major security issue.\n\n> If by default, `require('foo')` executes `foo.lua` from CWD, then yes we need to plug that.\n\nAs it currently stands, `require('foo')` **is unsafe to run in an untrusted directory**. I believe this is serious enough that this issue should be moved out of the backlog and be a priority for 0.12.2 (and potentially to a 0.11.8 release).",
